# Discord Chat Analysis

## 1. Summary
The chat segment shows minimal technical discussion. One user (biaxus) reported an issue with the EVM plugin for ElizaOS, mentioning they followed the official documentation but the agent didn't recognize the plugin after installation and configuration. Another user (wire) directed them to the dev support channel. There were several questions about the project status, with community members confirming the team is still active and pointing to GitHub as evidence. The chat clarified that ElizaOS is the agent framework with the ticker $ai16z (token address HeLp6NuQkmYB4pYWo2zYs22mESHXPQYzXbB8n4V98jwC). Users mentioned upcoming developments including "elizacloud" and "clanktank." Overall, the chat contained more general conversation and price discussion than technical content.

## 2. FAQ
Q: Is there any official people here? I encounter an issue when using EVM plugin. (asked by biaxus) A: Unanswered
Q: Did the team fall out why is price so depressed? (asked by samdanodono) A: Team intact as they've been from the start, nothing changed (answered by Dr. Neuro)
Q: Are there any big upcoming plan or development they are working towards? (asked by samdanodono) A: Many things, including elizacloud, clanktank upcoming, daily newschannel, jedi council (answered by Rick)
Q: Is elizaos and ai16z under the same token or not? (asked by samdanodono) A: elizaOS is the agent framework, with the ticker $ai16z (answered by Kenk)
Q: What happened to partners chat? (asked by Zapdart) A: Go to verification channel (answered by Kenk)
Q: How much did you have to hold to be partner again? (asked by samdanodono) A: 100k to post, 10k to view (answered by Zapdart)

The discussion primarily focused on plugin development and configuration issues in ElizaOS. Several users encountered problems with specific plugins like EVM, Gaianet, and Ollama. The Gaianet plugin appears to be missing in the current version, with suggestions to build a custom plugin following the Venice plugin as an example. There were also discussions about OpenRouter configuration issues, remote Ollama calls across a LAN, and knowledge embedding challenges. Users shared configuration examples and troubleshooting steps, particularly for the Ollama plugin with different models. # Analysis of "fun" Channel Chat

## 1. Summary
The chat primarily revolves around discussion of ELI5, a token in the auto.fun ecosystem. Community members express enthusiasm about ELI5's potential growth, comparing it to other successful tokens like Rugproof. There's significant interest in developing lore around ELI5, with user cjft mentioning plans to build character narratives. A community member (Dr. Neuro) provides a detailed explanation differentiating ELI5 from AI16z, describing ELI5 as an AI that explains complex concepts simply, while AI16z is portrayed as a team of AI agents that build and execute tasks. The chat suggests ELI5 has significant community support and potential for growth, with some members speculating it could reach $100M+ valuation. There are also brief mentions of potential AI functionality for ELI5 and hints at future developments. User wire suggests auto.fun should focus on "proof of project" rather than memes, positioning itself as an AI launchpad for startups.

# Discord Chat Analysis - "core-devs" Channel

## 1. Summary:
The discussion primarily focused on developing browser extensions and applications similar to Cluely, with an emphasis on privacy and local processing. The team explored using Chrome's desktopCapture API to create a browser extension that can listen to calls and provide AI assistance without requiring users to create separate accounts. They discussed building a comprehensive ecosystem with desktop apps, mobile apps, and browser extensions that would sync context across devices while maintaining privacy. The team also considered monetization strategies, including a token-based credit system for cloud services while keeping local features free. There was debate about prioritizing game development versus cloud infrastructure. A partnership with Wolfram was mentioned, requiring plugin development with LaTeX handling for mathematical outputs. The team noted the impressive performance of GLM-4.5, an open-source model outperforming most competitors except Sonnet and Opus. They also discussed agent-to-agent (A2A) protocols and the importance of creating infrastructure rather than focusing solely on developing useful agents.

## 2. FAQ:
Q: How do you listen to calls for the browser extension? (asked by R0am | tip.md) A: Using Chrome's desktopCapture API, similar to how Loom works. (answered by cjft)
Q: How would you implement cross-device context transfer? (asked by R0am | tip.md) A: Using something like Supermemory/zep/mem0 that's self-hostable with a tunnel on top for local memory that follows you. (answered by R0am | tip.md)
Q: Did you extend the hackathon? (asked by Borko) A: Yes, it will be extended today, this will be the last extension. (answered by jin)
Q: For bootstrap logging, should it enforce its own filepath structure or emit events for plugins? (asked by Odilitime) A: It should use the existing logger core functionality, with bootstrap emitting to the normal logger. (answered by cjft)

## 3. Help Interactions:
Helper: sam-developer | Helpee: shaw | Context: Implementation of Cluely-like functionality | Resolution: Shared an open-source version of Cluely (glass) that was previously mentioned
Helper: R0am | tip.md | Helpee: shaw | Context: On-ramp payment solutions for the platform | Resolution: Offered to help with CDP product that provides USDC on Base with swap API for game tokens and embeddable wallet functionality
Helper: cjft | Helpee: Odilitime | Context: Bootstrap logging implementation question | Resolution: Suggested using the existing logger core functionality rather than creating a new logging system
